REPLACE INTO "events" VALUES (32,'conference_major','1989-06-01','1989-06-07','','Youth Message Facing Our Future',NULL,'Youth and Educators from schools worldwide that had responded to the campaign and appeal 1988. The conference report stressed the topics of Education, Role of the United Nations, Conflict Resolution, Environmental concern, Security - Armament.\r\n\r\nConference Message:\r\n<bold>\"We, the international youth, believe in our strength to create a better future. At the Life-Link seminar we have decided to work for the creation of an international network of contacts and communication between schools all over the world. Such a network of Friendship-Schools would serve as a means to improve the awareness of the threats to our existence such as weapons of mass destruction and the degradation of our environment. It would also stimulate the willingness to work in a creative and positive way for the elimination of such threats.\"</bold>',NULL,NULL,752,'no');
REPLACE INTO "events" VALUES (33,'conference_major','1992-06-01','1992-06-07','','Down to Earth!',NULL,'The structure of Life-Link Friendship-Schools was discussed. Principal steps to run a project at a schools was outlined. Issues of importance for Life-Link are Environment, Social service programmes, Convention on the Rights of the Child, Security. \"If You are not part of the solution, You are part of the problem\"',NULL,NULL,752,'no');
REPLACE INTO "events" VALUES (34,'conference_major','1994-06-01','1994-06-07','','Global Environment Campaign 1992-1994',NULL,'Youth and Educators from schools representing 21 countries worldwide reported on actions performed at schools within the Global Environment Campaign 1992-94.\r\nHuman Rights issues also had a prominent role at this conference. A Youth Action Plan was launched 1994-1996 YAP',NULL,NULL,752,'no');
REPLACE INTO "events" VALUES (35,'conference_major','1995-06-01','1995-06-07','','Statement on School-Twinning. UN 50',NULL,'A Life-Link conference including 45 students-teachers-educators from 19 countries all continents during 4 days. 11 higher educational institutes were represented. 13 embassies from Stockholm were represented at the opening and closing ceremonies. The title of the conference was \"Youth Communication and Cooperation for Human and Global Common Security\".\r\n\r\nA school-twinning programme will benefit: Youth, Education, the Earth. A computer electronic mail conference on School-Twinning was inaugurated at this conference. The conference was recognized in the United Nations Programme \"UN 50 Years\", and by the UN Secretary General Mr Boutros Boutros-Ghali and by UNESCO officials.',NULL,NULL,752,'no');
REPLACE INTO "events" VALUES (36,'conference','1996-06-01','1996-06-07','','European Youth Voices on Nuclear Weapons and Common Security',NULL,'11 youth representing six European countries discussed: Our Concerns about Nuclear Weapons\r\nOur Thoughts about Security and Common Security\r\nWhat can WE do?\r\n\r\nThe roles of education, and individuals taking responsibility were stressed. The report from this small conference was send to the Heads of States in nuclear weapons countries.',NULL,NULL,752,'no');
REPLACE INTO "events" VALUES (37,'conference_major','1996-06-01','1996-06-07','','A People Friendlier Earth Campaign 1994-1996',NULL,'51 Schools from more than 25 countries sent their reports on performed projects within the \"APFE\" campaign. 20 schools from 18 countries were represented at the conference.\r\n\r\nA Life-Link youth declaration 1996 was worked out:\r\n<bold>\"We the global youth can work together. Without youth cooperation the future is bleak, with it the future can be bright. Unfortunately previous generations, in many respects, have let us down. We, as the youth today, are the future and must therefore unite for the benefit of forthcoming generations. We, the Life-Link youth, stress the importance of cross-cultural and cross-geographical contacts between teenagers.\r\n\r\nThe best way to achieve this is by twinning schools. Schools should try to revolve their twinning around specific projects dealing with issues that are vital for our time. Any issue that a schools would like to discuss, must be regarded as an important issue. A very important aspect when working with the projects is that practical and fun actin is taken.\r\n\r\nHaving met at this conference we realise the importance of personal meetings and their creating of cultural understanding. Therefore we recommend twinning schools to include a student exchange in their friendship process. \r\n\r\nWe also strongly recommend Life-Link to continue with the international youth conferences. We would like to introduce you to a few certain points that we feel are crucial to make the path towards improved common seuciryt on our only planet easier to walk along.\r\n\r\nWe urge teenagers across the globe and their guiding grown-ups, to join us in our call for a future world characterised by Peace, Common Security and Justice.\"</bold>\r\n\r\nAn extensive Life-Link Manual 1996: \"School-Twinning and Project Management for Common Security\" was worked out.',NULL,NULL,752,'no');
REPLACE INTO "events" VALUES (38,'conference_major','1997-06-01','1997-06-07','','Start School-Twinning & School-Networking at Every School from Year 2000',NULL,'A conference statement was worked out by 44 delegates (18 youth, 20 educators, 6 lecturers) representing 20 international organisations, covering 5 continents.\r\n\r\nNine points were stressed\r\n- Education\r\n- UNESCO Recommendation\r\n- Youth Engagement\r\n- Encouragement of Teachers\r\n- School-Twinning and School-Networking\r\n- Projects and Campaigns\r\n- Vital Issues for our common Future\r\n- Information and Communication Technology\r\n- Ethics: Caring and Sharing.\r\n\r\nThe report was sent out to all UN and UNESCO national missions.\r\nThe report was handed over personally to United Nations Secretary General Mr Kofi Annan visiting Uppsala Sweden a few days after this conference.',NULL,NULL,752,'no');
REPLACE INTO "events" VALUES (39,'conference_major','1998-06-01','1998-06-07','','Caring and Sharing Actions at Schools Worldwide 2000+',NULL,'Time for Action - Join the Campaign! 53 delegates (37 youth and 16 teachers) from 20 schools in 14 countries reported on performed Caring and Sharing Actions within the campaing 1996-98. 39 school-twinning relations were formed during this conference.\r\n\r\nProjects that were presented:\r\n- Enviro Care\r\n- TEMA & Ecology - Treeplanting\r\n- Conflict Resolution on the Demarcation Line in a Divided City\r\n- IDEAS - International Day of Environmental Action and Service\r\n- Blue Danube River Project (UNESCO programme)\r\n- Life-Link at the School of Peace for Young People - Colombia\r\n- Life-Link Project - exchange programmes\r\n- Ecology Club\r\n- Humanitarian Project\r\n- \"Scarabaeus\" Baltic School & Environment Club\r\n- Project Week\r\n- Eco-School Project 2000\r\n- Life-Link Recycling and Drug projects\r\n- \"CYP\" project Sarajevo\r\n- The Footsteps Scheme Kenya\r\n- Human Rights Cracow\r\n- Exchange Programme Moscow - Sweden.\r\n\r\nA new campaign approaching the new Millenium was launched.',NULL,NULL,752,'no');
REPLACE INTO "events" VALUES (40,'conference_major','1999-06-01','1999-06-07','','Youth Caring and Sharing Actions at Schools Worldwide 2000+',NULL,'This conference with 54 delegates (35 youth, 13 teachers, 6 lecturers and staff) edited more than 1500 proposals sent to Life-Link Sweden from 179 schools in 55 countries.\r\n\r\nA draft on a Life-Link Manual on peace actions was formulated: Care for Myself - Care for Others - Care for Nature - Lets Get Organised.\r\n\r\n<bold>A Manual in English language was then edited and printed and made available on www.life-link.org , entitled: Youth Caring and Sharing Peace Actions at Schools Worldwide Year 2000 and 2000+.</bold>\r\n\r\nA Youth Statement 1999 was formulated ending: <bold>\"Believing in ourselves, together we can and we will make a difference\"</bold>. A conference for year 2001 was proposed.',NULL,NULL,752,'no');
REPLACE INTO "events" VALUES (41,'conference_major','2001-06-01','2001-06-07','','Report 2001 - Youth Peace Actions and Projects at Schools Worldwide 2000+',NULL,'82 delegates (46 youth, 36 teachers and educators) from 21 countries, 5 higher educational institutions (Ministries of Education or UNESCO offices), were represented at this conference.\r\n\r\nYouth peace actions inspired by the Life-Link Manual and Campaign 2000+ were reported in plenary and poster sessions. Workshops with youth and teachers in separate groups were performed and has been the agenda at previous conferences. Observers from 7 embassies in Stockholm joined the opening and closing ceremonies. Conferences for 2002 were drafted in order to promote the Life-Link programme in Russia, Arab region and Eastern European countries.\r\n\r\nA Life-Link flyer was drafted. The Life-Link homepage was re-edited by youth from Romania, showing the true international cooperation within this decentralised Life-Link youth and schools programme.','conferences/2001',NULL,752,'no');
